1. Introduction
1.1 Overview
This report references the Triangle, NextDate, and Commission programs set to cover various BlackBox
approaches as part of the software testing process. The goal is to evaluate the software program against
the system specifications and set of expected performances to detect defects. Approaches used in this
review include boundary value analysis, equivalence class partitioning, and decision table methodologies.
1.2 Purpose
The primary purpose of the report is to document various activities and testing results as part of error
detection in order to identify gaps and defects in contrast to what the program is set to perform, which
may necessitate corrective actions.
1.3 Testing Techniques
Black box testing techniques are primarily adopted for the purpose of this exercise, output is observed
based on designed test input with no prior knowledge of the code structure. The goal is to exercise
end-system behavior to uncover various responses regarding expected and unexpected cases.
1.3.1 Boundary Value Analysis
Tests are designed to include representatives of boundary values in a range, worst-case scenarios are
applied where all possible variable combinations of values are taken into consideration.
1.3.2 Equivalent Class Partitioning
Partition is used to categorize input data of equivalent classes in order to develop sophisticated test cases
with a better focus and less redundancy. It generates fewer test cases to capture important runtime
components that need to be focused on.
1.3.3 Decision Table Testing
Input conditions are examined to help identify the true/false set of test cases through input combinations
to better assist the decision-making process with the presented cause-effect relationship in the data.

2.6 Critical issues discovered - Triangle
1) Failed cases observed for Isosceles mistakenly classified as scalene whenever side b=c. The program yields
success Isosceles output only when side a=b or a=c. There is no comparison made between side b=c that
brought the failure.
2) The program does not handle decimal values, number rounding is taken place where 0.5 or great are
rounded to the next whole number integer, distribute the incorrect result
3) No checking in place against the Triangle Inequality Theorem to validate the correctness of the triangle.
Incorrectly classifying false triangles as Scalene or Isosceles triangle. The following side validation should
be conducted
i) a + b > c
ii) a + c > b
iii) b + c > a
4) No error catches in place in response to null values, the system converts null values into numeric value 0
proceeding with the calculation.
5) Worst Case Boundary Value Analysis test cases failed to include the Right Triangle scenario
6) An error exists in the test case document indicating a supposed isosceles triangle as scalene, the system
yielded the correct output value
2.7 Triangle Test Statistics
An estimated time of 160 minutes was spent for testing including test case design, execution, and analysis.
While Boundary Value Analysis executed the highest number of test cases, however, it demonstrated a
similar problem both Equivalent Class Partition Decision Table had caught with few numbers of test cases.
In this case, the worst-case analysis provides a comprehensive view of the program in identifying faults,
but may not be necessary.

3.6 Critical issues discovered - Next Date
1) Based on the result, it seems the program understands the number of maximum days in the
month. However, there is no checking for days beyond the month cap number, proceeding with
the calculation to the next month. For example, any input greater than 30 or 31 of the month is
recognized as the end of the month, where the program proceeds to the 1st day of the next
month.
2) The program does not proceed to increase the year count when its end of the year December 31
3) There is no catch for negative inputs, the program proceed the addition on negative numbers on
years and date instead of terminating with an error
4) Decimal values are not handled properly, the system rounds decimal to next number integer to
proceed with the calculation instead terminate with an error
5) The system requires the month to be fully spelled and does not handle month abbreviations such
as (Jan, Dec..etc)
3.7 Next Date Test Statistics
An estimated time of 85 minutes was spent for testing including test case design, execution, and analysis.
Boundary value analysis tends to reveal more defects but additional tests were needed to reveal that the
program actually had a record number of days for each month but was a termination problem that
preceded the next month.

4.7 Commission Test Statistics
An estimated time of 45 minutes was spent for testing including test case design, execution, and analysis.
Boundary value analysis tends to reveal more defects for the commission problem since it covers the vast
majority of test scenarios. This type of software is not well served by the decision table because there is
very little decisional logic adopted in the calculation. Equivalent Class Partitioning would be the best
testing strategy for the problem, however, very few cases were prepared in the document.

1. Introduction
1.1 Overview
This report focuses on structure testing with references to the white box testing techniques performed on
the NextDate program. The goal is to create an error-free program by evaluating the data flow within the
source code. Approaches used in this exercise primarily focus on path testing, ensuring test cases are
designed where all independent paths are executed at least once.
1.2 Purpose
The primary purpose of the report is to identify existing errors within the source code of the NextDate
program. Test cases are designed and documented to cover all possible independent paths software
executes.
1.3 Testing Techniques
Structure testing techniques are primarily adopted for the purpose of this exercise, program source codes
are translated into control flow graphs representing execution nodes. Based on the Control Flow Graph,
test cases are designed and executed to uncover errors presented at independent paths.
2. Structure Testing
2.1 Control Flow Graph
The following Control Flow Graph uses graph notation to represent all paths that may be
traversed through the program execution.

1. Introduction
1.1 Overview
This report uses white box testing technique to identify data flow path coverage for the NextDate
program. The goal is to create an error free program by evaluating the data flow within the source code.
Approaches used in this exercise primarily focus on the du-path testing, ensuring test cases are designed
where all independent variables are used appropriately.
1.2 Purpose
The purpose of the data flow testing is to explore the code by identifying how values are retrieved and
used for all data variables. The goal of the testing is to reveal:
- variables that are declared but not used in the program
- variable redefined multiple times before its used
- using variable that is not declared
1.3 Testing Techniques
du-path testing techniques are primarily adopted for the purpose of this exercise, the NextDate program
source code is revealed to uncover a set of variables used in the program. The define and usage of these
variables are identified to construct test cases for the testing coverage.
